<subSubSection pageId="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[707,1194,441,1339]" pageId="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,836,627,648]" pageId="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2014" box="[967,1104,627,648]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maracayensis">
<emphasis box="[967,1104,627,648]" italics="true" pageId="7">maracayensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
speciesgroup, only in specimens of this species is the pronotal disc red and the pronotal arch infuscated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[707,1194,441,1339]" pageId="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,916,707,728]" pageId="7">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 
<quantity box="[1026,1115,707,728]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="7" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[707,785,733,754]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="7" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[798,854,733,754]" pageId="7">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation box="[935,1007,733,754]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="21.[197,237,1489,1508]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,194,1458]" captionTargetId="figure-75@21.[172,1193,192,1465]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs. 92–97. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 92) P. helvinus; 93) P. maracayensis; 94) P. modestus; 95) P. bilineatus;" pageId="7">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1021,1135,733,754]" pageId="7">Integument</emphasis>
: Cranium light brown, antenna mostly black, capitular antennomeres with small yellow patches; pronotum light brown, infuscated on arch and base; elytra black; femora and tibiae yellow; pterothorax and abdomen black. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1035,1088,866,887]" pageId="7">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes not as wide as frons (13:16); funicular antennomeres moderately expanded, 7 
<superScript attach="left" box="[971,986,914,928]" fontSize="6" pageId="7">th</superScript>
antennomere long (
<figureCitation box="[714,789,946,967]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="7">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,888,946,967]" pageId="7">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum transverse (42:38), lateral tubercle very prominent (
<figureCitation box="[1050,1131,972,993]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="18.[175,215,1395,1414]" captionTargetBox="[151,1155,183,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-114@18.[151,1172,183,1383]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs. 48–61. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 48) P. helvinus; 49) P. maracayensis; 50) P. modestus; 51) P. bilineatus; 52) P. calceatus; 53) P. corumba; 54) P. flavolimbatus; 55) P. ovatus; 56) P. wappesi; 57) P. amplus; 58) P. flavoapicalus; 59) P. gilvus; 60) P. hermani; 61) P. orellana." pageId="7">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold gradually narrowed to elytral apex, asetiferous punctures prominent to elytral apex. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[707,808,1052,1073]" pageId="7">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tegminal lobes and phallic apex as in 
<figureCitation box="[735,809,1079,1100]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="20.[175,215,1170,1189]" captionTargetBox="[164,629,189,1147]" captionTargetId="figure-461@20.[151,638,183,1159]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs. 76–91. Pujoliclerus species, aedeagi. 76) P. helvinus; 77) P. bilineatus; 78) P. calceatus; 79) P. corumba; 80) P. flavolimbatus; 81) P. ovatus (tegmen only); 82) P. wappesi; 83) P. gilvus; 84) P. hermani; 85) P. casselorum; 86) P. catarina (phallus only); 87) P. argus; 88) P. aspigalbus; 89) P. flora; 90) P. posticalis; 91) P. pallidus." pageId="7">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[707,1194,441,1339]" pageId="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,831,1105,1126]" pageId="7">Variation.</emphasis>
The infuscation on the pronotal arch is more prominent in the 
<typeStatus box="[955,1049,1132,1153]" pageId="7">paratypes</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[707,1194,441,1339]" pageId="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,899,1158,1179]" pageId="7">Natural History.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[955,996,1158,1179]" pageId="7">type</typeStatus>
series emerged from the cactus 
<taxonomicName box="[810,900,1185,1206]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Cereus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="corine">
<emphasis box="[810,900,1185,1206]" italics="true" pageId="7">C. corine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
during July.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[707,1194,441,1339]" pageId="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,861,1212,1233]" pageId="7">Distribution.</emphasis>
